post_text: Students at Osmond ARE allowed to bring birthday treats in to celebrate their birthdays. As a slight change to our Smart Start Plan, please be advised that birthday treats MUST be store bought and individually wrapped! Nothing homemade or from a store bakery, such as cupcakes or donuts are allowed! Things like Twinkies, Little Debbie treats, Ding Dongs, etc are some examples of acceptable items that can be brought in. Please call the school if you have any questions!

Greetings Parents/Guardians!

Osmond Elementary's Smart Start Plan Summary can be found here:

https://osmond.lcsd2.org/2020/08/06/osmond-elementary-smart-start-plan-summary/

This summary includes procedures that all students, parents, and staff will need to follow in order to open our doors and make face-to-face learning a reality. The adjustments to our typical day at school are made in correlation with directives from the Lincoln County Public Health Office. As these health orders are updated, we will make adjustments to our plan as needed. Thank you for your understanding and support during this interesting time and please call the school if you have any questions! THANK YOU!!

post_text:
Forwarded from Lincoln County School District #2 :

Lincoln County School District #2 school closure! Late this afternoon, Sunday, March 15, Governor Mark Gordon and State Superintendent Jillian Balow recommended that all schools are closed to students through at least April 3. LCSD#2 is following the recommendation of Governor Gordon and Supt. Balow and will close all schools until April 6. LCSD#2 Administration will release further plans after meetings are concluded Monday morning. Updates will be on our websites, social media and SVI. District administrators will be contacting staff over the next few hours.

Forwarded from Lincoln County School District #2 :

Lincoln County School District #2 school closure! LCSD#2 is following the recommendation of Governor Gordon and Supt. Balow and will close all schools until April 6. LCSD#2 Administration will release further plans after meetings are concluded Monday morning. Updates will be on our websites, social media and SVI. District administrators will be contacting staff over the next few hours.

HALLOWEEN REMINDERS!

Students are welcome to wear their costumes all day tomorrow! Please come in your costume with hair, makeup, etc all ready as the students will NOT be allowed to leave class to take care of these things. Also please remember no masks, weapons, or inflatable costumes as students need to be able to comfortably be at school in costumes all day! Also don’t forget our Pumpkin Patch if you choose to participate!! Prizes are involved 🙂 Just remember pumpkins can’t ride on the bus to or from school! Please have all pumpkins picked up by 3:30 as they will be being discarded at such time!

Thank you for helping make this a super fun day for our kiddos!!

post_text:
Valentines Day is tomorrow. Please no flowers, stuffed animals, or chocolates delivered to students at school!
Let me explain – In years past we have had flowers, stuffed animals, and chocolates delivered to students from their families. It is wonderful and exciting for those who receive them. Problem is, all students aren't lucky enough to have something sent. Looking into those young eyes brimming with excitement as they come to the office checking to see if the latest delivery is for them and then seeing those same eyes convey disappointment/sadness is hard to describe. Life is tough enough, please save your celebration for home.

post_text: Wicki-up Broadcasting Club (WBC) is Osmond’s own news program. Students meet after school where they learn to be ace reporters as they scour the school for upcoming events, tidbits of interest, and anything newsworthy. Besides finding the story, they write their own copy, find supporting photos or video, and use our state of the art equipment to record the broadcast. You will be able to keep current with what’s happening at Osmond Elementary as you watch our reporters develop their talents. oekids.lcsd2.org/podcast

Parents,
Our PTC is looking for help with the banking program and would love volunteers.

What would it entail?

Committing to a few Tuesday mornings for an hour.
Being at the school from 9:50-10:35.
Taking deposits from the students during their morning recess.
Delivering the completed deposits to the three local banks.

If you are interested in helping us out, please call the school at 307-885-9457 and we will forward your information.

Wow, can you believe it's the last week of September? My drive to work reminds me of Albert Camus's quote, "Autumn is a second spring when every leaf is a flower."

The week of September 26, 2016 has only a couple of announcements to share:

School photos are Thursday, 9/29/16. Student pictures will begin at 8:10 with preschool pictures following sometime after 10:00 a.m.

Thursday will also be the fundraiser deadline! Please turn in packets as we need to get the orders turned in to have them filled by Thanksgiving. And, thanks for helping fund our ski program!

Friday, 9/30/16, is a No School Friday! Enjoy the fall!!!

Wow, I'm a day late entering this weeks activities. Sorry!
Today, Tuesday, September 20, the PTC is starting Banking Day during first recess.
With the help of our local banks and the Osmond PTC, we are offering a student savings program. This program will teach students important financial management skills which will benefit them for a lifetime. Our awesome PTC will have someone at the school during first recess every Tuesday to represent the banks and take deposits which they will then deliver to the banks. Student's that make 40 deposits by May 12, 2017 will earn an additional $25 from their bank(s).

This week at Osmond:
PTC meeting Thursday @10. All interested parents are invited.
Deadline for returning Dry Creek Academy sign-ups is Friday, 9/9/16.
As this year is the 15th anniversery of September 11th, we will be having an informative assembly Friday morning. Susan Kertesz, is a children's author and has published a book called "Harvey" that is a true story that happened on September 11th. The assembly will be presented in a way that strengthens students and gives them ways to rise to their own challenges.
